Our dataset from kaggle (https://www.kaggle.com/fedesoriano/stroke-prediction-dataset) is intended to be used for stroke prediction. The dataset contains 5000 instances and 11 feature columns and one target attribute, high liklihood of stroke. Our dataset is highly imbalanced in our stroke feature column and is split 95/5% 0 (not likely): 1 (very likely) of a stroke event. To prevent our model from overestimating that someone is unlikely for stroke we will upsampled our training data. The data contains clearly relevant features to stroke prediction such as age, gender, hypertension, heart disease, glucose level, bmi, and smoking history. However, we have additional interesting categorical features that may influence stroke likelihood as well such as ever married, work type, and residence type. We use all of these features and add a wide network to our models for memorization of common cross column encoded data.

SMOTE Oversampling</br>

Drawbacks of oversampling: if you have classes with very few instances you might put too much emphasis on the fact that those samples belong to a specific class.

Benefits: Providing our model with a balanced daatset will allow it to properly learn how to differentiate those with strokes from others without the model reflecting many more non-stroke predictions just because we had few stroke samples.

Drawbacks source: https://www.machinecurve.com/index.php/2020/11/10/working-with-imbalanced-datasets-with-tensorflow-and-keras/

Final Datasets¶

Now that we have upsampled our dataset to reflect a balanced dataset for our target feature, a stroke event, we can describe our testing and training data. As seen by the df.info of our training data, we can see that all 13 of our columns are represented by either label encodeded numerical values or standard scaled values for continous data such as age, avg_glucose_level, and bmi. We are using all of the columns and data given to us as each gives us important data relevant to predicting strokes. The only new variable we have created is our BMI range category which we plan on using in our cross-columns for our wide network. We believe that people in very high BMI ranges tend to hav increased stroke risk and we hope out wide network will be able to detect this by using the cross columns and lable encoded categories. To be clear: we did not upsample our testing data, only our training data. Testing data is sacred, cannot touch.

cross_columns = [['hypertension','heart_disease', 'smoking_status_int'],
                 ['ever_married','work_type_int', 'gender'],
                ['bmi_range_int', 'heart_disease'],
                   ['bmi_range_int', 'gender']]
cross_col_df_names = []
for cols_list in cross_columns:
    # encode as ints for the embedding
    enc = LabelEncoder()
    
    # 1. create crossed labels by join operation
    X_crossed_train = X[cols_list].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(str(x)), axis=1)
    X_crossed_test = test_X[cols_list].apply(lambda x: '_'.join(str(x)), axis=1)
    
    # get a nice name for this new crossed column
    cross_col_name = '_'.join(cols_list)
    
    # 2. encode as integers
    enc.fit(np.hstack((X_crossed_train.to_numpy(),  X_crossed_test.to_numpy())))
    
    # 3. Save into dataframe with new name
    X[cross_col_name] = enc.transform(X_crossed_train)
    test_X[cross_col_name] = enc.transform(X_crossed_test)
    
    # keep track of the new names of the crossed columns
    cross_col_df_names.append(cross_col_name)

The output above shows all of the cross columns we have created for our dataset. Hopkins Medical School published storke risk factors and listed heart disease, gender, and smoking as major risks. Those attributes are present in this dataset and have significant correlations to increased risk of stroke when an individual has multiple high risk factors.

A study published on Circulation Research from 2017 states the following, “The investigators enrolled 3000 patients with stroke and found that hypertension, current smoking, waist-to-hip ratio, diet risk score, regular physical activity, diabetes mellitus, binge alcohol consumption and psychosocial stress and depression were all associated with stroke risk.” (1) They also highlight that a combination of these stroke risk factors continutes to increase stroke risk. This indicates that combining high risk factors could help improve our model by giving Wide branches to use memorization.

The first group we decided to combine was hypertension, heart_disease and smoking_status_int. We decied to combine these together because they are all high risk stroke factors from these studies and significant research points to their compunding effect on increasing stroke risk (2).

The second set of cross columns is ever_married, work_type_int and gender. Because personal life and stress can be attributed to things like hemmoraging and high stress, it is a valuable reason to consider work and marriage as major stressors. We also are interested in gender in this particular cross column because it is a major consideration in marraige and could help separate some specific cases of high stroke risk.

The third set of cross columns is bmi_range_int and heart_disease. We decided these were fitting to combine because while heart disease is a cause of stroke, obesity can often be a cause of both heart disease and strokes and both are immediate health risks if at extreme levels (3). We believe this potential overlap in these two columns could help our wide network see a relationship between having high BMI levels and heart disease and more obviously low risk individuals who are not at high BMI and don’t ave heart disease. Although we want to understnad what causes stoke, seeing what attributes with low levels or certain combinations that do not commonly lead to strokes are also valuable information.

The last cross product was to combine gender and bmi_range_int because frankly a team member has a hunch that overweight men are more likely to have strokes than overweight women.

Splitting our BMI feature into categories classified by expert knowledge and the scientific community helps us add an additioanl level of knowledge and reason to splitting the feature a certain way and allows us to nearly cross categorical columns with ranged numeric data.

(1) - https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/full/10.1161/circresaha.116.308398

(2) - https://www.heartandstroke.ca/healthy-living/reduce-stress/stress-basics#:~:text=Stress%20can%20cause%20the%20heart,a%20heart%20attack%20or%20stroke

(3) - https://www.webmd.com/stroke/guide/stroke-causes-risks#2 </br>

Validation¶

In our prediction task, it is extremely important to remember exactly what the implications of our model could mean - if we predict someone to not be at risk of stroke when they truly are, we could be putting someone’s life at risk. For this reason, we must focus on improving our false negatives scores and attempt to minimize false negatives to as close to 0 instances as possible.

Looking at other metrics, we are OK with having high false positives in our algorithm as long as it means the false negatives are low. Meaning, if we overpredict the risk of stroke feature to be true (1), then we will be more likely to meet our condition of minimizing false negatives. However, like most trade offs, we are not planning to use this caveot to predict all individuals as high risk, as that would largely defeat the purpose of the algorithm and potentially give people stress (doctor tells you you’re at risk for stroke, when you may not actually be, doesn’t that freak you out? Maybe cause you stress you didn’t need?).

Right now, only 4% of our dataset is at risk of a stroke. That means that achieving a high accuracy would be very easy. If you were to predict everybody as not at risk for a stroke then the accuracy would be about 96%. That is why our main focus is not accuracy, but rather minimizing any false negatives. Given these conditions for what we need to minimize, we will largely base our performance on the Recall of predicting class 1 in stroke prediction, attempting to maximize this value and bring it as close to 1.00 as possible (this is really just (1 - Type II error). Additionally, since measuring recall of both of the 2 predition classes (0 or 1) in essence is a reflection of accuracy, we will also use accuracy as a metric for performance in our classifier, behind Recall of prediction class 1.

Splitting our Data and Cross Validation Method¶

Before upsampling our data, it is important to split the dataset into testing and training data so we do not interfere with the validation set before running models and using minority upsampling to increase the amount of stroke instance features in our training data.

For the majority of the program / lab, we will have split our data using the pandas .sample() function to take our input df and return 20% randomly selected. This serves as our validation set for most of the lab.

However, we feel that the best method to truly train and optmize our model would be to use 5-fold cross validation testing. By using this form of validation, our model is training on a (slightly) new dataset and verifying the model on a new set of testing data (that was or will be used for training as well). This cross validation ensures that every observation from the original dataset has the chance of appearing in training and test set. Additionally, it works well for training and testing models with smaller datasets (as this data set has less than 10,000 instances). Although we are not using the 5-fold cross validation for each model in the lab, we will use it later in the lab. First, we will use cross validation on models with varying numbers of layers. This will help us determine which model performs the best. After getting this "best performing model", we will compare it to the MLP, again using the 5-fold cross validation on the MLP as another way to compare their perfomance.

    # track what the maximum integer value will be for this variable
    # which is the same as the number of categories
    N = max(X[col].max(),test_X[col].max())+1
    
    # this line of code does this: input_branch[:,idx]
    x = tf.gather(input_crossed, idx, axis=1)
    
    # now use an embedding to deal with integers as if they were one hot encoded
    x = Embedding(input_dim=N, 
                  output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), 
                  input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(x)
    
    # save these outputs to concatenate later
    crossed_outputs.append(x)
    

# now concatenate the outputs and add a fully connected layer
wide_branch = concatenate(crossed_outputs, name='concat_1')
wide_branch = Dense(units=1,activation='sigmoid', name='combined')(wide_branch)

model = Model(inputs=input_crossed, outputs=wide_branch)

model.compile(optimizer='sgd',
              loss='mean_squared_error',
              metrics=['accuracy'])

model.fit(X_crossed_train,
        y, epochs=10, batch_size=32, verbose=1)

def runModel(model, optimize, iterations, batchSize):
    model.compile(optimizer=optimize,
              loss='mean_squared_error',
              metrics=['accuracy'])

    # lets also add the history variable to see how we are doing
    # and lets add a validation set to keep track of our progress
    history = model.fit([X_train_crossed,X_train_cat,X_train_num],
                    y, 
                    epochs=iterations, 
                    batch_size=batchSize, 
                    verbose=0, 
                    validation_data = ([X_test_crossed,X_test_cat,X_test_num],y_test))
    yhat = np.round(model.predict([X_test_crossed,X_test_cat,X_test_num]))
    acc_mod = mt.accuracy_score(y_test,yhat)
    print("Accuracy: " + str(acc_mod))
    print(mt.confusion_matrix(y_test,yhat))
    print(mt.classification_report(y_test,yhat))
    cm = mt.confusion_matrix(y_test, yhat, labels=classes)
    disp = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix=cm, display_labels=classes)
    disp.plot()
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,4))
    plt.subplot(2,2,1)
    plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'])

    plt.ylabel('Accuracy %')
    plt.title('Training')
    plt.subplot(2,2,2)
    plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'])
    plt.title('Validation')

    plt.subplot(2,2,3)
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
    plt.ylabel('Training Loss')
    plt.xlabel('epochs')

    plt.subplot(2,2,4)
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
    plt.xlabel('epochs')
    return cm, yhat

def makeModel(denseUnits, denseActivation, finalActivation):  
    # get crossed columns
    X_train_crossed = X[cross_col_df_names].to_numpy()
    X_test_crossed = test_X[cross_col_df_names].to_numpy()

    # save categorical features
    X_train_cat = X[categorical_headers_ints].to_numpy() 
    X_test_cat = test_X[categorical_headers_ints].to_numpy() 

    # and save off the numeric features
    X_train_num =  X[numeric_headers].to_numpy()
    X_test_num = test_X[numeric_headers].to_numpy()


    # we need to create separate lists for each branch
    crossed_outputs = []

    # CROSSED DATA INPUT
    input_crossed = Input(shape=(X_train_crossed.shape[1],), dtype='int64', name='wide_inputs')
    for idx,col in enumerate(cross_col_df_names):

        # track what the maximum integer value will be for this variable
        # which is the same as the number of categories
        N = max(X[col].max(),test_X[col].max())+1


        # this line of code does this: input_branch[:,idx]
        x = tf.gather(input_crossed, idx, axis=1)

        # now use an embedding to deal with integers as if they were one hot encoded
        x = Embedding(input_dim=N, 
                      output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), 
                      input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(x)

        # save these outputs to concatenate later
        crossed_outputs.append(x)


    # now concatenate the outputs and add a fully connected layer
    wide_branch = concatenate(crossed_outputs, name='wide_concat')

    # reset this input branch
    all_deep_branch_outputs = []

    # CATEGORICAL DATA INPUT
    input_cat = Input(shape=(X_train_cat.shape[1],), dtype='int64', name='categorical_input')
    for idx,col in enumerate(categorical_headers_ints):

        # track what the maximum integer value will be for this variable
        # which is the same as the number of categories
        N = max(df_train[col].max(),df_test[col].max())+1

        # this line of code does this: input_branch[:,idx]
        x = tf.gather(input_cat, idx, axis=1)

        # now use an embedding to deal with integers as if they were one hot encoded
        x = Embedding(input_dim=N, 
                      output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), 
                      input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(x)

        # save these outputs to concatenate later
        all_deep_branch_outputs.append(x)

    # NUMERIC DATA INPUT
    # create dense input branch for numeric
    input_num = Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],), name='numeric')
    x_dense = Dense(units=denseUnits[0], activation=denseActivation[0],name='num_1')(input_num)

    all_deep_branch_outputs.append(x_dense)


    # merge the deep branches together
    deep_branch = concatenate(all_deep_branch_outputs,name='concat_embeds')
    for i in range(1, len(denseActivation)):    
        deep_branch = Dense(units=denseUnits[i],activation=denseActivation[i], name='deep{}'.format(i))(deep_branch)

    # merge the deep and wide branch
    final_branch = concatenate([wide_branch, deep_branch],
                               name='concat_deep_wide')
    final_branch = Dense(units=1,activation=finalActivation,
                         name='combined')(final_branch)

    model4 = Model(inputs=[input_crossed,input_cat,input_num], 
                  outputs=final_branch)
    return model4

from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold
kfold = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5,shuffle=True, random_state=1).split(X, y)
denseUnits = [22,100,50] #numbers, need at least 1
denseActivation = ['relu','relu','relu'] #sigmoid, relu
finalActivation = 'relu' #sigmoid, relu
optimize = 'adagrad'
iterations = 50
batchSize = 32

scores = []
recalls = []
for k, (train, test) in enumerate(kfold):
    #print(k,len(train),len(test))
    #Make Model

    # get crossed columns
    X_crossed = X[cross_col_df_names].to_numpy()
    
    X_train_crossed = X_crossed[train]
    X_test_crossed = X_crossed[test]
    #X_test_crossed = test_X[cross_col_df_names].to_numpy()

    # save categorical features
    X_cat = X[categorical_headers_ints].to_numpy()
    
    X_train_cat = X_cat[train]
    X_test_cat = X_cat[test]
    #X_test_cat = test_X[categorical_headers_ints].to_numpy() 

    # and save off the numeric features
    X_num = X[numeric_headers].to_numpy()
    
    X_train_num =  X_num[train]
    X_test_num = X_num[test]
    #X_test_num = test_X[numeric_headers].to_numpy()


    # we need to create separate lists for each branch
    crossed_outputs = []

    # CROSSED DATA INPUT
    input_crossed = Input(shape=(X_train_crossed.shape[1],), dtype='int64', name='wide_inputs')
    for idx,col in enumerate(cross_col_df_names):

        # track what the maximum integer value will be for this variable
        # which is the same as the number of categories
        N = max(X[col].max(),test_X[col].max())+1


        # this line of code does this: input_branch[:,idx]
        x = tf.gather(input_crossed, idx, axis=1)

        # now use an embedding to deal with integers as if they were one hot encoded
        x = Embedding(input_dim=N, 
                      output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), 
                      input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(x)

        # save these outputs to concatenate later
        crossed_outputs.append(x)


    # now concatenate the outputs and add a fully connected layer
    wide_branch = concatenate(crossed_outputs, name='wide_concat')

    # reset this input branch
    all_deep_branch_outputs = []

    # CATEGORICAL DATA INPUT
    input_cat = Input(shape=(X_train_cat.shape[1],), dtype='int64', name='categorical_input')
    for idx,col in enumerate(categorical_headers_ints):

        # track what the maximum integer value will be for this variable
        # which is the same as the number of categories
        N = max(df_train[col].max(),df_test[col].max())+1

        # this line of code does this: input_branch[:,idx]
        x = tf.gather(input_cat, idx, axis=1)

        # now use an embedding to deal with integers as if they were one hot encoded
        x = Embedding(input_dim=N, 
                      output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), 
                      input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(x)

        # save these outputs to concatenate later
        all_deep_branch_outputs.append(x)

    # NUMERIC DATA INPUT
    # create dense input branch for numeric
    input_num = Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],), name='numeric')
    x_dense = Dense(units=denseUnits[0], activation=denseActivation[0],name='num_1')(input_num)

    all_deep_branch_outputs.append(x_dense)


    # merge the deep branches together
    deep_branch = concatenate(all_deep_branch_outputs,name='concat_embeds')
    for i in range(1, len(denseActivation)):    
        deep_branch = Dense(units=denseUnits[i],activation=denseActivation[i], name='deep{}'.format(i))(deep_branch)

    # merge the deep and wide branch
    final_branch = concatenate([wide_branch, deep_branch],
                               name='concat_deep_wide')
    final_branch = Dense(units=1,activation=finalActivation,
                         name='combined')(final_branch)

    model = Model(inputs=[input_crossed,input_cat,input_num], 
                  outputs=final_branch)
    #Model Made
    
    #Now time to run the model
    model.compile(optimizer=optimize,
              loss='mean_squared_error',
              metrics=['accuracy'])
    
    # lets also add the history variable to see how we are doing
    # and lets add a validation set to keep track of our progress
#     print("Printing y")
#     print(y.unique)
#     print(y_testCV.unique)
    y_trainCV = y[train]
    y_testCV = y[test]
    history = model.fit([X_train_crossed,X_train_cat,X_train_num],
                    y_trainCV, 
                    epochs=iterations, 
                    batch_size=batchSize, 
                    verbose=0,
                    validation_data = ([X_test_crossed,X_test_cat,X_test_num],y_testCV))
#     print(y_testCV.unique)
#     print("Here")
    #yhat = np.round(model.predict(test_X))
    yhat = np.round(model.predict([X_test_crossed,X_test_cat,X_test_num]))
    #print(type(yhat))
    #yhat = np.array(yhat, dtype='int')
    #print(type(yhat))
    #print(yhat)

    #y_testCV = np.array(y_testCV, dtype='int')
#     print(yhat.unique)
#     print(y_testCV.unique)
#     print(np.unique(yhat))
#     print(np.unique(y_testCV))
    acc_mod = mt.accuracy_score(y_testCV,yhat)

    cm = mt.confusion_matrix(y_testCV, yhat, labels=classes)
    recall = cm[1][1]/(cm[1][1]+cm[1][0])
    print("Recall: ", recall)

Going to run the McNemar test comparing the NN vs. the MLP now

In [143]:
# Example of calculating the mcnemar test
from statsmodels.stats.contingency_tables import mcnemar
# define contingency table
table = [[nn_test[1][1], nn_test[1][0]],[mlp_test[1][1], mlp_test[1][0]]]
# calculate mcnemar test
result = mcnemar(table, exact=True)
# summarize the finding
print('statistic=%.3f, p-value=%.1f' % (result.statistic, result.pvalue))
# interpret the p-value
alpha = 0.05
if result.pvalue > alpha:
    print("Same proportions of errors (don't reject H0)")
else:
    print('Different proportions of errors (reject H0)')

statistic=12.000, p-value=0.0
Different proportions of errors (reject H0)

# Example of calculating the mcnemar test
from statsmodels.stats.contingency_tables import mcnemar
# define contingency table
table = [[nn_test[1][1] + nn_test[0][0], nn_test[1][0] + nn_test[0][1]],[mlp_test[1][1] + mlp_test[0][0], mlp_test[1][0] + mlp_test[0][1]]]
# calculate mcnemar test
result = mcnemar(table, exact=True)
# summarize the finding
print('statistic=%.3f, p-value=%.1f' % (result.statistic, result.pvalue))
# interpret the p-value
alpha = 0.05

    print("Same proportions of errors (don't reject H0)")
else:
    print('Different proportions of errors (reject H0)')

statistic=235.000, p-value=0.0
Different proportions of errors (reject H0)

In the first McNemar test we are only comparing the models on their ability to classify strokes. We can see that they are very statistically different despite having similar accuracies. This has to do with the fact that the MLP had a much lower recall score when it came to classifying stokes. In the second McNemar test we are looking at the models based on their overall classification abilities. We can see that again, they are very statistically different. Their accuracies are the same but outside of that, the models classify the test dataset quite differently.

The ROC curves shows us that our wide and deep neural network is performing better than the MLP. While both the MLP and our neural network start at the same rate of tradeoff between true positives and false positives, the MLP flattens out before our model. It flattens out almost to an angle of 45 degrees, which indicates almost randomness in its ability to classify. Our model reaches closer to the top left corner before flattening out which means it was still learning before approaching that line of randomness. The area under the curves score for both models is similar, but our model has a slightly higher area under the curve. While this can mean that our model has issues with specific classes, it is generally a better model than the MLP. According to science direct, an AUC score of at least 0.7 is considered acceptable for a model.

Exceptional Work¶

For this part we will create a model with Embedding layers, capture the weights of the first layer after the Embedding and cross multipy it with corresponding training dataset, then use sklearn's t-distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding (TSNE) to do dimentionality reduction and try to visualize the results.

In [151]:
X_train_cat = X[categorical_headers_ints].to_numpy() 

# and save off the numeric features
X_train_num =  X[numeric_headers].to_numpy()

all_branch_outputs = [] # this is where we will keep track of output of each branch

input_cat = Input(shape=(X_train_cat.shape[1],), dtype='int64', name='categorical')
for idx,col in enumerate(categorical_headers_ints):
    
    # track what the maximum integer value will be for this variable
    # which is the same as the number of categories
    N = max(df_train[col].max(),df_test[col].max())+1
    
    
    # this line of code does this: input_branch[:,idx]
    x = tf.gather(input_cat, idx, axis=1)
    
    # now use an embedding to deal with integers as if they were one hot encoded
    x = Embedding(input_dim=N, 
                  output_dim=int(np.sqrt(N)), 
                  input_length=1, name=col+'_embed')(x)
    
    # save these outputs to concatenate later
    all_branch_outputs.append(x)
    
# HERE IS THE ADDING OF AN INPUT USING NUMERIC DATA
# create dense input branch for numeric
inputs_num = Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],), name='numeric')
x_dense = Dense(units=22, activation='relu', name='num_1')(inputs_num)
    
all_branch_outputs.append(x_dense)

# now concatenate the outputs and add a fully connected layer
final_branch = concatenate(all_branch_outputs, name='concat_1')
final_branch = Dense(units=6, activation='relu', name='combined_1')(final_branch)
final_branch = Dense(units=1, activation='sigmoid', name='combined_2')(final_branch)

model = Model(inputs=[input_cat,inputs_num], outputs=final_branch)

model.compile(optimizer='sgd',
              loss='mean_squared_error',
              metrics=['accuracy'])
model.summary()

We can see in this plot clear grouping of the different classes, the two classes do not overlap and we can easily differentiate them in this plot over the other. Also the clusters are denser in class no-stroke than in class stroke. One similarity between the two classes, is that class no-stroke exist at smaller values of dimension 1 and larger values of dimension 2. The clusters of no-stroke appear to take uo the 1st quadrant (top left) of the visual. However, clusters of class stroke appear to exist in quadrants 2, 3, and 4 (bottom left, top right, and bottom right). The values of the dimensions for strokes seem to be proportional. For example, strokes exist where both dimensions take on smaller values. Then, as dimension 1 increases, the value for dimension 2 also increases for where strokes exist.
